An individual has a functional disability if the individual has a severe, chronic disability that:
is attributable to a mental or physical impairment or a combination of mental and physical impairments, including a head injury;
is likely to continue indefinitely;
results in substantial functional limitations in at least three of the following areas of major life activity:
self-care;
receptive and expressive language;
learning;
mobility;
self-direction;
capacity for independent living; and
economic self-sufficiency; and
reflects the individual's need for a combination and sequence of special interdisciplinary or generic care, treatment, or other services that are:
lifelong or of extended duration; and
individually planned and coordinated.
